==English==
===Etymology===
Old English ''[[wegan]]'', from Germanic.  Cognate with Scots ''[[wey]]'', Dutch ''[[wegen]]'', German ''[[bewegen]]''.

===Pronunciation===
*{{AHD|wā}}, {{IPA|/weɪ/}}, {{SAMPA|/weI/}}
*:'''Homophones''': [[way]], [[whey]]
*:[[Rhymes:English:-eɪ|Rhymes: -eɪ]]

===Verb===
{{en-verb}}

# {{transitive}} To determine the weight of an object. 
# {{transitive}} ''(metaphorical)'' To determine the intrinsic value or merit of an object
#:''You have been '''weighed''' in the balance and found wanting.''
# {{transitive}} To consider a subject. 
# (''Nautical'') {{transitive}} To raise an anchor free of the seabed.
# {{transitive}} To be equal in heaviness to.
#:''I weigh ten and a half stone.''

